value.value: This is the name for the fermenting mass made by mashing shubo (or just yeast in the case of kobo-jikomi), steamed rice, koji and water together. Immediately after mashing, moromi is like a solid mass of swollen rice grains, but it begins to soften as saccharification proceeds.
Moromi is a soft solid material fermented with raw material contained in a liquid brewed to make soy sauce, sake, etc.
